Quick look at one of my sketchbooks from 2015 

This was a large moleskin book. I used Prisma Premier markers and brush pens. I didn't even learn digital art yet at this time. 

I was less technically skilled and more fearless creatively back then. I also had more fun. 

My goal is to bring this feel back. 

#art #sketchbook #moleskine #prismacolor #artist #drawing #sketchbooktour #throwback #flowers

Less gimmics, 
and less focus on the algorithm.

Simplicity, focus, and passion. 

I'm here to create art to connect with your emotions and bring us together. 

There's a lack of empathy and in many ways we are more divided than ever. My mission going forward is bringing people together around the topic of art and its positive impact on mental health. 

As an artist that is mostly self taught, I also want to teach the next generation of artists what I've learned. 

If my art speaks to you, please buy it and share it so that I can build and achieve my mission.  If there isn't a piece that has connected with you yet, please leave constructive feedback so I can fill that space in your art collection. 

Thanks your reading, 
Love to all 
-David

Here's the rest of the animation. 

It's based on a phrase my Grandma would always tell me : "Your stumbling block is your stepping stone" 

I hand drew it in Procreate and added post effects in CapCut.

You don't have to have formal training in animation to create something. 

I was watching a dope YouTube video about 2d animation in fighting games when I was inspired to create this. 

The animation concepts I needed to get started:

Key frames 
In-betweens
Less frames = snappy movement 
More frames = fluid movement 

How I put it together:

I mapped out the animation using key frames, then I  added in- betweens where necessary to dictate the timing. 

Keep learning with passion and patience 🤙🏾
